truths. Rather, for Wallace, philosophy and literature are intertwined ways of experiencing and expressing the world that emerge from and amplify each other. The book does not advance a fixed or homogenous interpretation of Wallace’s oeuvre but instead offers an investigative approach that allows for a variety of readings. The volume features fourteen new essays by prominent and promising Wallace scholars, divided into three parts: one on general aspects of Wallace’s oeuvre – such as his aesthetics, form, and engagement with performance – and two parts with thematic focuses, namely ‘Consciousness, Self, and Others’ and ‘Embodiment, Gender, and Sexuality’.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPhilosophy in literature. 4aLiterature Studies 2022. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aContemporary American Fiction.  aDavid Foster Wallace.  aPhilosophy and Literature.1 aArdovino, Adriano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArdovino, Adriano, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaggio, Guido, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoorman, Lola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrossi, Angelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes-Brady, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarchese, Lorenzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasiero, Pia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasiero, Pia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMattoscio, Mara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPitari, Paolo, econtributor.4ct